@deykno87 Eh, I don't think every movie has to follow some kind of set of rules about how to please your audience, that's just gonna dumb down both art and audiences. Sometimes, people don't know what they want until they get it. That's the thing about great art, you don't get it unless you have a lot of failed experiments on the way.

I feel like the point of this movie was specifically not to stick with any one specific narrative regarding the event of a nuclear war. Because all the different scenarios the movie sets up as possibilities are very real possibilities - if unlikely. I think it would just be going against its ambition to paint a hyper-realistic but also highly ambiguous what-if scenario. Saying "Oh it was the North Koreans with the help of character X, now we're gonna shoot them back" I at least think would just make the film feel kind of silly and less grounded.

I liked the ambiguity of the ending. My big problem was, as Drinker also pointed out, that not much is added or revealed in the two additional run-throughs of the basic plots. The first section was absolutely fantastic but each subsequent part just feels less interesting because I already know all the crucial details and I'm already attached to the characters from the first part and I'm just disappointed that I'm not following them anymore.
